nt of   Hatch  , with voicing of the final consonant.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Hecke  ."]},{"name":"Hatcher","meanings":["English (southern): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate, from Middle English <i>haccher(e)</i>, a derivative of <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’. This normally denoted a gate marking the entrance to a forest or other enclosed piece of land, sometimes a floodgate or sluice-gate. Compare   Hatch  ."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sarah Hatch was born about 1240, in Europe, her father, Galfrid Geoffrey Hatch, was 42 and her mother, Alicia de Aller, was 36. She had at least 1 son with William Worlington."},"et":{"about 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1205":"1205","1255":"1255","1200":"1200","before 1240":"enne 1240","1240":"1240","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Europe":"Europe","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1240–":"noin 1240–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1255":"1255","1200":"12